For example, at {{ill|Yasaka Shrine|ja|八坂神社}}, {{ill|Susanoo|ja|素戔嗚尊}} is enshrined as the main deity, with his consort {{ill|Kushinadahime|ja|櫛稲田姫命}} to the east and their "{{ill|Hachiōji Gongen|ja|八王子権現|Note=I’m not sure the proper translation. But it is not Eight pillar mikogami, that is an error based on the counter for gods|Lt=|lt=Eight mikogami}}" to the west. At {{ill|Kasuga Taisha|ja|春日大社|Kasuga-taisha}}, the auxiliary shrine "{{ill|Wakamiya Shrine|ja|若宮社}}" enshrines {{ill|Ame-no-Oshikumone|ja|天押雲根命}}, the Mikogami of the main deity {{ill|Ame-no-Koyane|lt=Ame-no-Koyane-no-Mikoto|ja|天児屋根命}}.
The term "{{ill|Wakamiya|ja|若宮}}" usually refers to shrines dedicated to Mikogami. However, in some cases, it refers to newer shrines rather than deities themselves. Such shrines may enshrine the parent or ancestor deity of the main shrine, serve as {{ill|Otabisho|ja|御旅所}}, or be shrines established as a result of deity transfer ({{ill|Kanjō|ja|勧請}}). Therefore, not all Wakamiya shrines are dedicated to Mikogami.
